
[1]lump

   LUMP, n.

   1. A small mass of matter of no definite shape; as a lump of earth; a
   lump of butter; a lump of sugar.

   2. A mass of things blended or thrown together without order or
   distinction; as copper, iron, gold, silver, lead, tin, promiscuously in
   one lump.

   3. A cluster; as a lump of figs. 2Kings. 20.

   In the lump, the whole together; in gross.

   They may buy my papers in the lump.

                                 LUMP, v.t.

   1. To throw into a mass; to unite in a body or sum without distinction
   of particulars.

   The expenses ought to be lumped.

   2. To take in the gross.
